Can truth only be knowingly experienced subjectively?

This is a subtle philosophical point.

Everything you know comes through your own perspective. You never experience “reality itself” directly—you experience your perception of it.

So your knowledge is always mediated by:

* your senses,
* your brain,
* your memories,
* your concepts,
* your language.

That doesn’t necessarily mean reality itself is subjective.

A common distinction is:

* Ontology: What exists.
* Epistemology: How we know what exists.

Many philosophers would say:

* Reality may be objective.
* Our access to it is always partial and perspective-bound.

You might picture it like this:

Objective Reality
       ↓
Observation
       ↓
Interpretation
       ↓
Personal Experience

Each layer introduces limitations, but that doesn’t imply there is no underlying reality.

